## 1) Diagnosis — 8 Systemic UI Problems

| # | Symptom | Impact | Root Cause |
|---|---------|--------|------------|
| **D1** | Homepage feels like a marketing site; dashboard feels like a grey admin form tool | Users experience "two different apps" — erodes trust at the exact moment they go from "interested" to "doing work" | No shared design system. Homepage was built as a landing page (heavy typography, full-bleed), app screens were built as utility (minimal, function-first). No bridge between them |
| **D2** | Navigation has no active state, no breadcrumbs, no "you are here" | Users get lost after 2 clicks. On mobile it's worse: the side drawer shows 10 flat links with no grouping | Side drawer was built once and never iterated. No `usePathname()` comparison. No IA hierarchy reflected in the nav |
| **D3** | Employee action buttons overflow on mobile (4–5 unlabelled icon buttons per row) | Mystery meat navigation. Users don't know what the icons mean. On 360px screens the buttons physically don't fit | Actions were added incrementally (certificate, contract, edit, delete) without reconsidering layout at each addition |
| **D4** | Typography weight swings wildly: `font-black` (900) on homepage, `font-bold` (700) on dashboard, `font-semibold` (600) on forms, `font-medium` (500) in labels | No visual hierarchy rhythm. Everything competes for attention equally. Headings don't "feel" like headings | No typography scale was defined upfront. Each page was styled independently |
| **D5** | Missing CSS variable `--blue-500` used in trust badges | Silent rendering failure. Icons fall back to inherit/black. Looks broken but no one catches it because it's subtle | CSS custom properties were added ad-hoc. No lint or build-time check for undefined vars |
| **D6** | Dashboard compliance footer still says "SARS-compliant" (should be "eFiling-compliant" per legal review) | Legal risk. Contradicts the deliberate terminology change made in a previous conversation | String literals scattered in JSX. No central copy/i18n source of truth |
| **D7** | Settings page uses pill-tab navigation (unique in entire app); wizard uses a Stepper component (also unique); dashboard has no tabs at all | Three different "multi-section" patterns. User has to re-learn interaction patterns on every screen | No component library decision for "tabbed content." Each screen invented its own |
| **D8** | Dark mode partially works: side drawer always shows light logo; calculator hero has hardcoded `#27272a` gradient; green savings badge uses `bg-opacity-10` which doesn't compose with CSS vars in Tailwind v4 | Dark mode looks "half done." Undermines the premium feel and makes night-time use uncomfortable | Theme was bolted on after initial build. Not all components were audited for theme-awareness |

### "If we change nothing" risks:
- **Trust erosion**: A payroll app that looks inconsistent doesn't inspire confidence in its calculations
- **Compliance mistakes**: No guardrails means users can generate payslips with missing fields, invalid date ranges, or below-minimum wages with only a small inline warning
- **Support burden**: Users will email asking "where do I find X" because navigation doesn't guide them
- **Churn**: First-time users going from the polished homepage to the bare dashboard will feel bait-and-switched
- **Accessibility lawsuits/complaints**: Touch targets below 44px, no focus indicators on some interactive elements, colour contrast issues in dark mode

